            , <rs id="t18220417-60-viclabel303" type="occupation">butcher</rs>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t18220417-60-victim568 t18220417-60-viclabel303"></join>. On Sunday the 3d of March, the prisoner came into the shop, and asked for a loin of mutton, and took one up. I knew him before by his buying meat of us; I told him to go to the scales and have it weighed; he had it jointed, and was going out with it. Mr. Somers stopped him at the door, and asked if he had paid for it; he said Yes, he had paid Mrs. Somers. I said he had not; and took him to her, and she said he had not. I am positive it was never weighed.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18220417-60-person571">
                  SAMUEL 
                  SOMERS
               <interp inst="t18220417-60-person571" type="surname" value="SOMERS"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18220417-60-person571" type="given" value="SAMUEL"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18220417-60-person571" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I was in the shop. The prisoner never paid for the meat; my wife was by the scales; I was at the end of the shop with Allen.</p>
               <p>Q. Might he not have paid your wife, and you not see him - A. Not well. It was possible; 9 s. 8 d. were found on him.</p>
               <p>Prisoner's Defence. I went to buy the meat, and before I could make any answer Somers turned round, and called me a thief.</p>
               <p>
                  <rs id="t18220417-60-verdict304" type="verdictDescription">
